// RBSTR — Terrier access (sub-operation subdoc)
//
// STANDING subdoc, contract-first. The ACG home for the Terrier's access
// sub-operations — the atomic write / withdraw / read of a muniment. invest,
// divest, and rehearse are thin RBS0-side wrappers that compose these sub-ops
// and add their own non-terrier steps (the IAM bindings); the shared
// terrier-touch is defined once here, never restated in the wrappers (ACG:
// reference the home, don't recreate).
//
// Scope boundary: this subdoc defines the *access* — the verbs against the
// terrier. The Terrier *noun* (the resource contract: object format, bucket,
// managed-folder IAM grain) is a separate civic concept quoin that RBS0 seats
// with the other civic quoins (terrier, muniment, mantle, ...) at the head of
// the verb movement (M4). This subdoc references that noun; it does not define it.
//
// Not yet wired: registering the sub-operation quoins in the RBS0 mapping
// section and `include::`-ing this file into RBS0 (proximal to its include site,
// the standard operation-fragment treatment) is contract-first work of the M4
// terrier pace. Until then the civic words below are plain prose. Settled now:
// this subdoc's identity, and the atomic-write contract.

== Terrier access

The Terrier is a polity's durable, cloud-resident, authoritative record of which
citizen holds which mantle — one entry, a *muniment* recording (principal
subject, mantle held), per object (terrier noun quoin, forthcoming). Exactly
three sub-operations touch it:

* *write* a muniment — composed by the admission verb that grants a mantle;
* *withdraw* a muniment — composed by the admission verb that removes one;
* *read* muniments — the primitive rehearse composes, and the read side of the
  reconciliation diff.

write and withdraw share the atomic write-semantics below; read is a pure
list-and-fetch, no precondition.

=== Write semantics — atomic, server-adjudicated (settled)

Writes to the Terrier are made atomic by Cloud Storage itself. No Cloud Build
invocation, and no external lock, is involved.

* *Create is conditional on absence.* The object write carries the
  `ifGenerationMatch=0` precondition, so Cloud Storage performs the write only if
  no live object exists at that key. Concurrent creators race cleanly: one
  succeeds; the others receive `HTTP 412 Precondition Failed` and treat an
  already-present identical muniment as idempotent success.
* *Update is conditional on generation.* Where a muniment is rewritten rather
  than created, the write carries `ifGenerationMatch=<generation>` read
  beforehand — optimistic concurrency control. The write lands only if the object
  has not changed since the read; otherwise the 412 directs a read-and-retry.
* Cloud Storage guarantees these preconditions are evaluated atomically and free
  of race conditions. There is no multi-object transaction across muniments, and
  none is needed: each muniment is an independent object, so distinct governors
  writing distinct entries never contend, and the precondition covers the rare
  same-entry case.

Each write is therefore a single conditioned REST call: the bucket adjudicates
atomicity, the caller adds one query parameter and checks the HTTP code. This is
within bash's good case under BCG — glue over a service, carrying no lock logic
of its own.

=== Forthcoming — settled with the terrier noun quoin (M4)

Properties of the Terrier *noun*, not of its access; they settle when the noun
quoin lands:

* object granularity — per-entry versus per-subject — and the JSON shape of a
  muniment under a freshly-minted terrier sprue (this also fixes whether the
  generation-conditional update clause above is ever exercised, or whether
  writes are create-and-delete only);
* the physical bucket name, and where its constant is homed;
* the managed-folder grain and the IAM that scopes a governor's write to its own
  polity (today's `rbgb_` carries bucket-level IAM only).

// eof

